        spectropolarimetry in the bands of diatomic molecules. Our
        measurements at different rotational phases of a dwarf yielded
        one 5{\ensuremath{\sigma}} and two 3{\ensuremath{\sigma}}
        magnetic field detections. The observational data have been
        obtained with the LRISp polarimeter at the Keck observatory on
        2012 August 22 and 23. These data have been compared against
        synthetic full-Stokes spectra in the bands of the molecules CrH,
        FeH, and TiO, which have been calculated for a range of the
        stellar parameters and magnetic field strengths. Making use of
        {\ensuremath{\chi}} $^{2}$-minimization and maximum likelihood
        estimation, we determine the net magnetic field strength B (and
        not flux Bf) of LSR J1835+3259 to {\ensuremath{\sim}}5 kG with
        the help of the Paschen-Back effect in the CrH lines. Our
        measurements at different rotational phases suggest that the
        dwarf{\textquoteright}s surface might be covered with strong
        small-scale magnetic fields. In addition, recent findings of the
        dwarf{\textquoteright}s hydrogen emission and the Stokes V
        signal from the lower chromosphere indicate that its surface
        magnetic field might be changing rapidly giving rise to flare
        activity, similar to young dMe dwarfs. We substantiate the
        substellar origin of LSR J1835+3259 by making use of our own
        data as well as the photometric data from the all-sky surveys
        2MASS and WISE.}",
          doi = {10.3847/1538-4357/aa705a},
archivePrefix = {arXiv},
       eprint = {1705.01590},
 primaryClass = {astro-ph.SR},
       adsurl = {https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2017ApJ...847...60K},
      adsnote = {Provided by the SAO/NASA Astrophysics Data System}
}



